{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493184"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:59:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:59:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1246"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1246"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.37,0.18,0.11,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105890"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1246"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1246"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88364"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42258"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105890"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of severe left-sided colicky abdominal pain. He feels nauseated, but has not vomited. He had a similar episode of pain the previous week, but as it settled on its own accord, he did not seek help. His medical history includes gout and hypercholesterolaemia. His pain is now less severe than when it started earlier. On examination, his temperature 38.4 C, pulse rate 90/min, blood pressure 120/70mmHg and respiratory rate 19/min. He is tender in the left flank. A non-contrast CT scan shows left-sided hydronephrosis with an obstructing 7mm stone at the proximal ureteric junction. Urinalysis is positive for leucocytes and nitrates.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following analgesic regimens is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous morphine","Intramuscular ketorolac","Oral paracetamol","Subcutaneous fentanyl","Subcutaneous oxycodone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA non-steroidal anti-inflammatory agent (eg \u003Cstrong\u003Eketorolac\u003C/strong\u003E) is the recommended analgesic of choice in most cases of pain management with renal calculus disease. In this case, since the patient is nauseated and the pain is easing, the analgesic could be given parenterally or rectally. Evidence suggests that NSAIDs are equivalent to opioids (eg \u003Cstrong\u003Efentanyl\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxycodone\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Emorphine\u003C/strong\u003E) for the management of acute renal colic pain and have less side effects. Opioids are not preferred since they are associated with severe adverse effects like respiratory depression, nausea, and constipation. There is also a risk of addiction with narcotic analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients treated with NSAIDs are less likely to require rescue analgesia compared to the patients who received paracetamol. Hence, evidence recommends the use of NSAIDs (eg diclofenac, ketorolac) for pain management in renal colic. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory agents are as effective as opiates in providing analgesia in cases of renal colic."],"references":["Pathan S, Mitra B, Cameron P. A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis Comparing the Efficacy of Nonsteroidal Anti-inflammatory Drugs, Opioids, and Paracetamol in the Treatment of Acute Renal Colic. European Urology. 2018;73(4):583-595."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88364"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1246"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88364"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T18:09:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T18:10:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1246"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105890"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"headin